{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520795","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520795"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583746"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0.19,0.13,0.07,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6135"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44494"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6135"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"459"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"6893"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41829"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44494"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the emergency department with complaints of vomiting of blood and severe abdominal pain that radiates to the back. On examination, he appears pale and diaphoretic and is writhing around in pain. His vital signs include blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, heart rate 120/min, respiratory rate 22 breaths/min, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. Abdominal examination reveals epigastric tenderness with guarding. Laboratory investigations show a haemoglobin level of 80 g/L (normal range: 140-180 g/L). An emergency endoscopy finds a 3cm penetrating ulcer on the posterior wall of the stomach with adherent clots and visible pulsations.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely source of bleeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left gastric artery","Left gastroepiploic artery","Right gastroepiploic artery","Short gastric arteries","Splenic artery"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the clinical scenario described, including the endoscopic finding of a penetrating ulcer on the posterior wall of the stomach, the most likely source of bleeding is the \u003Cstrong\u003Esplenic artery\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPenetrating ulcers on the posterior wall of the stomach can erode into adjacent blood vessels, and the splenic artery is located close to this area. The splenic artery arises from the coeliac trunk and courses along the superior border of the body and tail of the pancreas towards the hilum of the spleen. Here it lies deep to the posterior wall of the stomach. If the ulcer penetrates deep enough to involve the pancreas, then it is also likely to involve the splenic artery or one of its branches. In these cases, it can lead to significant bleeding, resulting in haematemesis and hypovolaemic shock as suggested by this patient\u0027s clinical findings and laboratory results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe stomach is divided into cardia, fundus, body, and pylorus. The posterior relations of the stomach include the pancreas, spleen, left kidney, left adrenal gland, transverse mesocolon, and diaphragm. The peritoneum covering the posterior wall of the stomach forms the anterior layer of the lesser sac and is situated in the left upper quadrant of the abdomen. Arterial supply to the stomach is from the right and left gastric, right and left gastroepiploic, and short gastric arteries. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eright and left gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are related to the lesser curvature while the gastroepiploic arteries lie along the greater curvature. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eright gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E is a branch of the common hepatic artery and the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastric artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the celiac trunk. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eright gastroepiploic artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the gastroduodenal artery and the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft gastroepiploic artery\u003C/strong\u003E branches off from the splenic artery. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort gastric arteries\u003C/strong\u003E are 4 to 7 branches that arise from the splenic artery and supply the fundus of the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe left gastric artery is the other common source of bleeding from penetrating gastric ulcers located along the lesser curvature of the stomach. In the case of a posterior penetrating ulcer in the first part of the duodenum, the source of bleeding would be the gastroduodenal artery. This artery arises from the common hepatic artery and passes behind the first part of the duodenum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gastric ulcer bleeding can present with symptoms such as upper abdominal pain, haematemesis, melaena, or signs of hypovolaemic shock."],"references":["Shidahara, H., Fujikuni, N., Tanabe, K. et al. Massive bleeding from gastric ulcer-induced splenic artery pseudoaneurysm successfully treated with transcatheter arterial embolization and surgery: a case report. surg case rep 8, 196 (2022). https://doi.org/10.1186/s40792-022-01552-0","Pasumarthy L, Kumar RR, Srour J, Ahlbrandt D. Penetration of Gastric Ulcer into the Splenic Artery: A Rare Complication. Gastroenterology Res. 2009 Dec;2(6):350-352. doi: 10.4021/gr2009.10.1321. Epub 2009 Nov 20. PMID: 27990205; PMCID: PMC5139696."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-20T16:05:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T09:49:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6135"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44494"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","i